  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sustaining access to primary healthcare, mental health and psychosocial support, sexual and reproductive health, including treatment and care for victims of gender-based violence in Northern Uganda - Health response to the impact of the protracted South Sudanese crisis in Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With 17,827 new primary curative consultations from 16 July to 30 October 2018 (MDM-FR data), Bolomoni HC III continues to be an essential health facility within the settlement. As the result of the ongoing rehabilitation of facilities the HC currently plays a critical role in filling the gap of secondary healthcare at district level and in contributing to a reduced morbidity and mortality. While responding to a still fragile context still demanding assistance, the action will fit into a humanitarian-development nexus initiating a long-term process with the ultimate goal to handover the Bolomoni to the MoH by the end of 2020.To avoid creating a significant gap on the health service provision during 2019, Bolomoni HC III will keep providing the same level of services. MDM-FR will take over from MSF the IPD department on 1 January 2019. OPD and IPD services will be sustained and consolidated, including: sexual and reproductive health (SRH), including the response to gender-based violence (GBV) with the involvement of the local partner organization HRAPF regarding the provision of legal aid for GBV survivors; strengthened mental health and psycho-social services (MHPSS) with a focus on community based preventive approach; surveillance, treatment of diseases, prevention of communicable diseases and strengthened preparedness with a focus on disease outbreaks, including Ebola Virus Disease (EVD). In parallel and in close collaboration with the DHO, MDM-FR will organize the steps for the transition process and the full handover of Bolomoni HC III by the end of 2020. This entail planning the phased scaling-down of activities delivery, the future human resources set-up and the rehabilitation of the HC III. The handover will be done in alignment with the MoH standards for health care provision in Uganda.</narrative>
  </description>
